00:13:16,660 --> 00:13:19,540
 I think the European Union is going to collapse by 2030.

224
00:13:19,540 --> 00:13:21,660
 I don't think it can survive by 2030.

225
00:13:21,660 --> 00:13:28,540
 Even, um, Martin Armstrong says the same thing by 2030, 2035, it's going to collapse, uh, NATO as well.

226
00:13:28,540 --> 00:13:30,840
 Um, I think it's, it is the end of that.

227
00:13:30,920 --> 00:13:33,020
 There'll be new coalitions, uh, forming.

228
00:13:33,020 --> 00:13:37,600
 I think, you know, I think the, the, the Balkans, the Baltics, and the Slavs, they should come together and form their own union.

229
00:13:37,600 --> 00:13:40,740
 And, uh, there's some, you got some amazing people there.

230
00:13:40,740 --> 00:13:44,240
 I'll tell you, I spent a lot of time in Serbia and I had an organization in Romania.

231
00:13:44,240 --> 00:13:46,960
 I had, uh, the baby, the baby cradle Romania back in the day.

232
00:13:46,960 --> 00:13:49,560
 Um, spent some time in Bulgaria and Poland.

233
00:13:49,640 --> 00:13:54,160
 I lived in Poland, uh, love those countries, love the people, solid, easy going.

234
00:13:54,160 --> 00:13:55,900
 Matter of fact, funny story.

235
00:13:55,900 --> 00:14:02,580
 I was in Italy and two days ago, I was in this little village in a little street and a guy walked up to me and said, Steven, how you doing?

236
00:14:02,580 --> 00:14:07,040
 It was a guy that I hired in Poland back in 2015 to work for me.

237
00:14:07,040 --> 00:14:10,840
 Happened to be in Italy in a little village and a little street at the same time.

238
00:14:11,740 --> 00:14:20,720
 And he was like, he gave me a big hug, you know, and that for me, that's a, that's a symbolic of that's, that's the, that's the people that I love from the Balkan states, the Baltic states and the Slavic states.

239
00:14:20,720 --> 00:14:29,120
 It's just real, truly hard, heartfelt people who are hardworking and have a high integrity and want the best for the country and don't want to be messed with by the West or the East.

240
00:14:29,120 --> 00:14:31,200
 This is nice to hear.

241
00:14:31,200 --> 00:14:32,080
 Thank you very much.

242
00:14:32,080 --> 00:14:39,860
 But I have to ask you, you were an American soldier, uh, in the war in Iraq, in Operation Desert Storm, right?

243
00:14:39,940 --> 00:14:42,800
 1991, you even wrote a book about it.

244
00:14:42,800 --> 00:14:46,600
 You received a bronze star and then left the army.

245
00:14:46,600 --> 00:14:46,900
 Why?

246
00:14:46,900 --> 00:14:54,940
 Is that because of the little wounded Iraqi girl who changed your life or could you briefly share that story with us, please?

247
00:14:54,940 --> 00:14:55,880
 Yes, yes, sure.

248
00:14:55,880 --> 00:14:57,420
 So I, I, I went to war.

249
00:14:57,420 --> 00:14:58,400
 I was 23 years old.

250
00:14:58,400 --> 00:14:59,280
 I was ready to go.

251
00:14:59,280 --> 00:15:02,700
 And I knew when I went to war, I wasn't coming back because we were the front line.

252
00:15:02,700 --> 00:15:03,860
 We were the Calvary.

253
00:15:03,860 --> 00:15:07,700
 There was, you know, five tanks, five Iraqi tanks for every one of our tanks.

254
00:15:07,700 --> 00:15:08,640
 We knew we weren't coming back.

255
00:15:08,700 --> 00:15:11,460
 They told us, right, you will send everything home.

256
00:15:11,460 --> 00:15:12,460
 You're not coming back.

257
00:15:12,460 --> 00:15:13,740
 And I was fine with that.

258
00:15:13,740 --> 00:15:18,420
 And I knew that I was going to come back, uh, in a casket with American flag.

259
00:15:18,420 --> 00:15:19,300
 And I was okay with that.

260
00:15:19,300 --> 00:15:23,500
 So I went to war and I fought and I thought, this is how, this is what I'm here for.

261
00:15:23,680 --> 00:15:27,500
 But then I realized, um, what I was actually doing.

262
00:15:27,500 --> 00:15:35,520
 And I was, you know, I was pushing it down in the back of my head because if you don't, you could die.

263
00:15:35,520 --> 00:15:39,120
 If you're not, if you're distracted on the battlefield, you know, that's the end of your life.

264
00:15:39,840 --> 00:15:50,480
 Until one time I was at a checkpoint and this little girl came up in a pink dress, had her hands like this and, um, uh, she was burnt from head to toe.

265
00:15:50,760 --> 00:15:54,820
 And I sent her to the medics to get, to get bandaged up.

266
00:15:54,820 --> 00:16:00,060
 And when she came back out, I, I just, I just looked at her and she had the most beautiful smile I'd ever seen.

267
00:16:00,940 --> 00:16:04,960
 And the reason she smiled is because I got down on my knee and I gave her a little piece of candy.

268
00:16:04,960 --> 00:16:13,640
 And I remember sitting there thinking, this, this girl is burnt from head to toe, lost everything she's had.

269
00:16:13,640 --> 00:16:16,440
 And she's smiling because a piece of candy.

270
00:16:16,440 --> 00:16:18,960
 The hell am I doing here?

271
00:16:18,960 --> 00:16:20,800
 What in the hell am I doing here?

272
00:16:20,800 --> 00:16:22,220
 I did this.

273
00:16:22,220 --> 00:16:25,100
 And that was the end of my career.

274
00:16:25,100 --> 00:16:27,680
 I had to, I had to serve for another year and a half.

275
00:16:27,680 --> 00:16:30,320
 I finished the war off.

276
00:16:30,380 --> 00:16:31,360
 I didn't fight anymore.

277
00:16:31,360 --> 00:16:32,640
 It was, you know, ceasefire.

278
00:16:32,640 --> 00:16:37,460
 And we went home to Germany where I was stationed and I started my processing to get out of the military.

279
00:16:37,460 --> 00:16:42,220
 And I did everything I could to get out of the military honorably, which I did, but that was the end of it.

280
00:16:42,220 --> 00:16:44,300
 And I swore from that point on, no, no more of this.

281
00:16:44,300 --> 00:16:47,040
 I'm not going to support that anymore, but it's hard because it's an identity.

282
00:16:47,040 --> 00:16:52,200
 Remember when you joined the military in the United States army, the first, the bootcamp, isn't about learning how to be a military man.

283
00:16:52,200 --> 00:16:55,760
 It's about deprogramming us being a civilian.

284
00:16:55,760 --> 00:16:58,080
 They program you to be a killer.

285
00:16:58,080 --> 00:16:59,980
 They program you to be an assassin.

286
00:16:59,980 --> 00:17:04,020
 A murder, just to go out and do what you have to do without thinking about it.

287
00:17:04,020 --> 00:17:07,020
 And to get that out of your head is almost impossible.

288
00:17:07,020 --> 00:17:11,540
 To this day, I still have that, that, that programming that there is no stopping.

289
00:17:11,540 --> 00:17:13,040
 There is no giving up.

290
00:17:13,040 --> 00:17:14,980
 There, it doesn't matter what I do.

291
00:17:14,980 --> 00:17:17,060
 I fight until I win, period.

292
00:17:17,940 --> 00:17:21,100
 Whether it's in business, whether that's in a conversation, it doesn't matter.

293
00:17:21,100 --> 00:17:22,240
 I fight until I win.

294
00:17:22,240 --> 00:17:23,820
 And that was programmed into us.

295
00:17:23,820 --> 00:17:27,900
 So there's some good, there's some good things about that, but a lot of people get stuck in that identity.

296
00:17:27,900 --> 00:17:30,500
 So when they get out of the military, they can't assimilate.

297
00:17:30,500 --> 00:17:32,340
 They can't fit, which I couldn't either at the time.

298
00:17:32,580 --> 00:17:36,140
 It took me about 15 years to get back to being almost a normal person.

299
00:17:36,820 --> 00:17:37,980
 Did you feel guilty?

300
00:17:37,980 --> 00:17:39,780
 I still do to this day.

301
00:17:39,780 --> 00:17:41,980
 I think of her every single day since, since, since 1991.

302
00:17:41,980 --> 00:17:43,900
 There's not a day that goes by.

303
00:17:43,900 --> 00:17:44,480
 I don't think of her.

304
00:17:44,480 --> 00:17:51,360
 With your experience of war as an American, how do you view the wars in the world today?

305
00:17:52,680 --> 00:17:59,960
 I feel, if you look at it tactically and strategically, I say to myself, why are there even people on the battlefield anymore?

306
00:17:59,960 --> 00:18:02,620
 We got robots, we got drones, we got AI.

307
00:18:02,620 --> 00:18:04,720
 We don't need people on the battlefield anymore.

308
00:18:04,720 --> 00:18:07,480
 Why are we sending people into the meat grinder?

309
00:18:07,480 --> 00:18:09,520
 What's the reason for that?

310
00:18:09,520 --> 00:18:10,560
 Because of public opinion.

311
00:18:10,560 --> 00:18:11,620
 Because we need heroes.

312
00:18:11,620 --> 00:18:13,500
 Because we need this, oh, look what's happening.

313
00:18:13,500 --> 00:18:17,660
 If it was just robots, no one would care.

314
00:18:17,660 --> 00:18:20,720
 It would just be a slaughter on both sides, you know.

315
00:18:21,160 --> 00:18:23,980
 And it would be land for land or, or building for building.

316
00:18:23,980 --> 00:18:27,560
 But no one would be a hero and there'd be no personal stories.

317
00:18:27,560 --> 00:18:32,560
 And there'd be no Zelinsky standing there with his, you know, jogging suit on and saying, we will win.

318
00:18:32,560 --> 00:18:33,700
 You know, who's we?

319
00:18:33,700 --> 00:18:35,540
 Your robots and your, and your drones.

320
00:18:35,540 --> 00:18:37,580
 There is no we, right?

321
00:18:37,580 --> 00:18:40,600
 And so this is, it's a, it's a big show.

322
00:18:40,600 --> 00:18:41,220
 It's all for money.

323
00:18:41,220 --> 00:18:41,940
 It's all for power.

324
00:18:41,940 --> 00:18:46,980
 And it's just more and more and more money being pumped into the military industrial complex.

325
00:18:46,980 --> 00:18:50,220
 I mean, right now there's a slowdown because of the budget cuts or because of the,

326
00:18:50,220 --> 00:18:54,340
 in America because of the, they shut down the government because they couldn't get the budget passed.

327
00:18:54,340 --> 00:18:56,340
 And now it's slowing down.

328
00:18:56,340 --> 00:18:59,060
 Remember, the fiscal year ends in October.

329
00:18:59,060 --> 00:19:01,440
 And so they have to spend all that money in October.

330
00:19:01,440 --> 00:19:03,240
 And then November, December, no one spends.

331
00:19:03,240 --> 00:19:04,680
 January, it starts up again.

332
00:19:04,680 --> 00:19:08,780
 So in January, when it starts up again, there's going to be an influx of spending,

